Denote by $f(x,y)$ the function in hand. Using the denominator of the first fraction to substitute $1 =x - 1+y-1$ into the numerator and vice versa yields
$f(x,y) =  (x - 1)\left(\frac{x}{y - 1} +\frac{y-1}{x - 1} + 1\right) = \frac{x}{y - 1} +\frac{y-1}{x - 1} + (x-1+y-1) \ge 3 \sqrt[3]{xy-xy-y+1+x-1+y-1} = 3 \sqrt[3]{xy-xy}.$</think>
Notice that the minimum value of $xy$ is $x$ in the limit $y \to 1^+,$ while $x - 1$ is nothing else but $\frac{x}{y - 1} + \frac{y-1}{x - 1} = 1$ when $y \to 1^+.$ Thus,
\begin{align*}
&\frac{x}{y - 1} +\frac{y-1}{x - 1} + (x-1+y-1) \to 1 + 1 +2 = 4 \qquad \text{as} \qquad \left\{ \begin{array}{l}
y \to 1^+ \\
x \to 1^+ \end{array}\right.,
\end{align*}
and the answer is $\mathbf{4}.$
